That's a real phenomenon—but it has limits.

A useful way to frame it is:

> **Winning changes the interpretation of effort.**

When you're making progress, your brain tends to code the same workload as meaningful rather than draining. Motivation, anticipation, and a sense of momentum can make you *feel* like you have far more energy.

You see this in many contexts:

* Entrepreneurs working 16-hour days during a breakthrough.
* Athletes pushing through a championship run.
* Gamers playing all night while "in the zone."
* New parents finding reserves of energy during moments of purpose.

The work hasn't become physically free. Your perception of its cost has changed.

For Pantheon, you could even express it as a simple relationship:

[
\text{Perceived Fatigue} \approx \frac{\text{Workload}}{\text{Meaning} \times \text{Momentum}}
]

As meaning and momentum increase, the subjective burden of the same work decreases.

The flip side is important too: feeling energized by success doesn't eliminate biological needs. Sleep debt, stress, and physical fatigue still accumulate, even if they're temporarily masked. That's why people often "crash" after a major launch, competition, or mission—they've been borrowing against recovery.

So I like the phrase as a motivational maxim:

> **"You're never tired when you're winning."**

But I'd treat it as describing **experienced effort**, not actual physiology. In Pantheon terms, you might say that **high narrative coherence and forward momentum reduce perceived cognitive load**, while recovery remains a separate constraint that the system still has to respect.
